<p>FOXO4-DRI emerged from a 2017 study that asked a simple question: can you force zombie cells to self-destruct without harming healthy tissue? The answer, at least in mice, was yes. The peptide triggered selective apoptosis in senescent cells across multiple tissues, producing visible rejuvenation in aged animals.</p>

<p>For a deeper compound profile, visit <a href="https://peptidearc.com">PeptideArc</a>.</p>

<!-- ========== MECHANISM ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>How FOXO4-DRI Works: The p53 Liberation Strategy</h2>

<p>To understand FOXO4-DRI, you need to understand why senescent cells survive in the first place. The answer involves two proteins: FOXO4 and p53.</p>

<p>In healthy cells, p53 acts as a tumor suppressor and damage response coordinator. When a cell is too damaged to repair, p53 triggers apoptosis (programmed cell death). But in senescent cells, FOXO4 binds to p53 and traps it in the nucleus, preventing it from activating death signals (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28340339/">Baar et al., 2017</a>).</p>

